{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:47:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:47:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0,0,0.36,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52685"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5064"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22125"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22126"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESodium-glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2) inhibitors work by blocking glucose reabsorption in the proximal renal tubule, leading to increased urinary glucose excretion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely adverse effect of SGLT2 inhibitors based on this mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinary tract infections","Lactic acidosis","Weight gain","Hypoglycaemia","Peripheral oedema"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESGLT2 inhibitors work by blocking the sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 protein in the proximal renal tubule. This prevents reabsorption of filtered glucose, leading to increased glucose excretion in urine. \u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infections\u003C/strong\u003E are a common adverse effect of SGLT2 inhibitors because the increased urinary glucose creates an ideal environment for bacterial growth in the urinary tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with metformin, not SGLT2 inhibitors which are associated with euglycaemic ketoacidosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESGLT2 inhibitors actually cause weight loss, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight gain\u003C/strong\u003E, through caloric loss via glucosuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESGLT2 inhibitors work independently of insulin and rarely cause \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E on their own.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESGLT2 inhibitors cause osmotic diuresis and typically reduce fluid retention, thus making \u003Cstrong\u003Eperipheral oedema\u003C/strong\u003E an unlikely complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther complications related to the mechanism include genital mycotic infections, volume depletion, and electrolyte disturbances due to osmotic diuresis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2) inhibitors increase urinary glucose excretion by blocking glucose reabsorption in the proximal renal tubule.","High urinary glucose levels from SGLT2 inhibitors create an environment that promotes urinary tract infections.","Osmotic diuresis from increased urinary glucose can lead to volume depletion and electrolyte imbalances."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52685"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52685"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T09:18:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:18:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67233"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"